04201nam a22006615i 9780691201412DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20211991nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912014127 a10.1515/97806912014122doi  a(DE-B1597)612383  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aGN776.2.A1bB37 1992eb 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a746/.09/012201 aBarber, E. J.W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrehistoric Textiles :bThe Development of Cloth in the Neolithic and Bronze Ages with Special Reference to the Aegean /cE. J.W. Barber. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1991  a1 online resource (504 p.) :b4 color plates, 217 b&w illustrations, 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis pioneering work revises our notions of the origins and early development of textiles in Europe and the Near East. Using innovative linguistic techniques, along with methods from palaeobiology and other fields, it shows that spinning and pattern weaving began far earlier than has been supposed. Prehistoric Textiles made an unsurpassed leap in the social and cultural understanding of textiles in humankind's early history. Cloth making was an industry that consumed more time and effort, and was more culturally significant to prehistoric cultures, than anyone assumed before the book's publication. The textile industry is in fact older than pottery--and perhaps even older than agriculture and stockbreeding. It probably consumed far more hours of labor per year, in temperate climates, than did pottery and food production put together. And this work was done primarily by women. Up until the Industrial Revolution, and into this century in many peasant societies, women spent every available moment spinning, weaving, and sewing. The author, Elizabeth Wayland Barber, demonstrates command of an almost unbelievably disparate array of disciplines--from historical linguistics to archaeology and paleobiology, from art history to the practical art of weaving. Her passionate interest in the subject matter leaps out on every page. Barber, a professor of linguistics and archaeology, developed expert sewing and weaving skills as a small girl under her mother's tutelage. One could say she had been born and raised to write this book. Because modern textiles are almost entirely made by machines, we have difficulty appreciating how time-consuming and important the premodern textile industry was. This book opens our eyes to this crucial area of prehistoric human culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aBronze agezEurope. 0aBronze agezMiddle East. 0aNeolithic periodzEurope. 0aNeolithic periodzMiddle East. 0aTextile fabrics, PrehistoriczEurope. 0aTextile fabrics, PrehistoriczMiddle East. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691201412zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691201412423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691201412/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK